{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":6,"timestamp":1778701101,"nonce":"8M36SauTWSHtI7lKLQUYYZykcV0=","target":"08c49e39ce263e7b07908b24ad94a758fcf43594b8faaa29a030ef06be933349","message":"**Decision:** Production point-mass plant uses a first-order force filter with `tau_rise = tau_decay = 0.05 s` (50 ms) (see `scripts/train_minimax.py:295`).\n\n**Rationale:** 50 ms sits squarely within the consensus range for first-order muscle-force / activation time constants in motor-control models. Exact match to de Brouwer 2020 (same authorship lineage as cs2019). cs2019 itself used 60 ms, also well within range.\n\n| Source | τ (ms) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| de Brouwer, Jarrassé, Crevecoeur \u0026 Burdet 2020 (eNeuro) | **50** | Exact match to rlrmp; same authorship as cs2019 |\n| Crevecoeur, Scott \u0026 Cluff 2019 (J Neurosci) | **60** | First-order LP filter approximating muscle dynamics |\n| Zajac 1989 / Brown \u0026 Loeb (neuromusculoskeletal modelling) | **~40** | Standard activation time constant for EMG-to-force |\n| Todorov 2005 (Neural Comput) | (2nd-order filter; not directly comparable) | Muscle filter is 2nd-order with internal viscosity |\n\n**Verdict:** 50 ms is consistent with literature consensus (~40–60 ms range). No re-calibration motivated.\n\n**Step-response numerical note** (analytic, dt=10 ms, unit force command at t=0):\n- step 1 (10 ms): F/u = 0.20, v = 0.0020 m/s\n- step 2 (20 ms): F/u = 0.36, v = 0.0054 m/s\n- step 3 (30 ms): F/u = 0.49, v = 0.0097 m/s\n- step 4 (40 ms): F/u = 0.59, v = 0.0147 m/s\n- step 5 (50 ms): F/u = 0.67, v = 0.0199 m/s\n\nThis is the physics floor: even with an instantaneously-correct controller output, applied force only reaches ~63% of command by step 5. Relevant for interpreting post-go acceleration lags (see `c99ad9d` comment same session).\n\n**Companion decision record:** damping k=10 N·s/m — sibling issue `a04711e`.\n\n**Related work:**\n- `c99ad9d` — training-methods coord (post-go-lag comment cites this issue as the relevant decision record).\n- `2e5f643` — existing damping-sweep proposal; a τ-mini-sweep (50 → 25 → 10 ms at fixed k=10) would be a more direct test of the filter-bound-lag hypothesis than a k-sweep alone.\n- `1d9ae6f` — meta coord (placeholder cross-ref; ideally on a model-structure coord — see `4dabb63`).\n\n**Sources:**\n- de Brouwer et al. 2020 (eNeuro): https://www.eneuro.org/content/7/2/ENEURO.0514-19.2020\n- Crevecoeur, Scott \u0026 Cluff 2019: https://www.jneurosci.org/content/39/41/8135\n- Todorov 2005: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1550971/\n- Liu \u0026 Todorov 2007: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6673117/\n\nLabel: `feature` (decision record), `deferred` (not actionable work).","files":null}]}